ly was exhibited as the standard for "modern" Egypt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFamiliesxEgypt. 0aFamilieszEgyptxHistory. 0aFamily policyxCross-cultural studiesxHistoryxEgypt. 0aFamily policyzEgyptvCross-cultural studiesxHistory. 0aFamily policyzEgyptxCross-cultural studiesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a1919 egyptian revolution.  a19th century.  abourgeois family.  abritish colonial rule.  aclass changes.  acolonialism.  acultural perspective.  adomesticity.  aeconomic growth.  aegypt.  aegyptian nationalism.  aelite classes.  afamilial political culture.  afamily politics.  afamily structure.  agender norms.  agender roles.  ahistorians.  ahousehold structure.  amodern egypt.  amodernization.  amonogamy.  apolitical success.  apolygamy.  apostcolonialism.  aruling classes.  asocial changes.  asocial history.  asocial standards.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093753640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520937536/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles